			<title>The New Polymath - Audio Interview with Author Vinnie Mirchandani</title>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Enterpriseleadership-Audios/~3/462C4MtCLz4/ELO-Vinnie-Polymath-FINALEDIT3.mp3</link>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', 'Bitstream Charter', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/0470618302?tag=newflorenewre-20&amp;amp;camp=14573&amp;amp;creative=327641&amp;amp;linkCode=as1&amp;amp;creativeASIN=0470618302&amp;amp;adid=1A5TEGA3DPEHSTJYH767&amp;amp;"&gt;Polymath&lt;/a&gt;&amp;mdash;the Greek word for Renaissance Man&amp;mdash;is someone who excels in many disciplines. From Leonardo da Vinci to Benjamin Franklin, we have relied on polymaths to innovate and find creative solutions to the problems of the day. How would these Renaissance men and women manage our current technology bounty? Which disciplines would they choose to focus on? Would they work on the architecture of next-generation green cities, or focus on nanotechnology?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;The New Polymath&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is an enterprise that excels in multiple technologies&amp;mdash;infotech, cleantech, healthtech, and other techs&amp;mdash;and leverages multiple talent pools to create new medicine, new energy and new algorithms.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Enterpriseleadership-Audios/~4/462C4MtCLz4" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description>
